	<h3 id="question7"><b>How was the list of products created?</b></h3><br>
	<p>Historically, Ticketmaster has not had a clear understanding of the products within its portfolio, where they are hosted, and who is responsible for supporting them. This is due to the scale at which we operate, disparate data sources, and the lack of centralized repository for this information.</p><p>We have now captured knowledge of Ticketmaster’s products, broken down into components with basic information such as ownership, business priority, and category and stored the information in a centralized place called Product Search. We created this tool to prevent the data from going stale and ensure it was transparent and available to everyone. Product Search is a proof-of-concept to hold us by until the <a href="https://contegixapp1.livenation.com/confluence/display/LT/XB.9.2+Product+Inventory+Management">Product Inventory Management</a> system (PIM) is released. PIM is focused on delivering a centralized 'source of truth' for Ticketmaster products and asset associations, with the ability to extend to future attributes such as Tech & Team Maturity. We can use this data to gain insight and visibility into our infrastructure footprint and product portfolio to make better investment decisions.</p><p>Notice a theme here? All of the <a href="https://contegixapp1.livenation.com/confluence/display/LT/Goal+XB.9+-+Simplify+the+Software+Factory">Simplify the Software Factory</a> (SSF) initiatives are interrelated and designed to move the company towards continuous delivery.</p><br>

